Right now, the top miner is setting registration costs really high, which makes it hard for new miners to get started.

Do you really think new miners can compete with the current registration costs?

If you're already the top miner, you wouldn’t need to worry about this kind of mechanism.
In fact, it would motivate more miners to work harder to reach the top.
This approach would help prevent unnecessary increases in reg costs and make it easier for new miners to get started and compete.

it could actually improve the subnet’s algorithm performance and encourage more miners to participate.

@S@suke, why do you think that?

I support @Bob . It is impossible for new miners to enter this subnet. He is not speaking super-perfectly, but in fact he is speaking soundly. Only inexperienced miners or those who have already captured the subnet can argue with his main point.

I think this is same in other subnets. Only at the early stage of subnet launch, new miners can reg, as time goes, only experienced devs and winners survive.
This is the truth of life.

But there is no reason for complaining about this because the winners already did their best and doing their best more than the losers even this moment.

I've been mining in this subnet for over a month and got some success.
However, the registration costs are still a burden, mainly because of some bad miners who keep registering (even though it dereg their own miners). - just like @Just do it pointed out before.

That said, I believe experienced miners like us can still thrive under the new system, as long as our algorithms are solid.

In this regard, I actually think @Bob's idea isn't bad at all - in fact, it might be pretty good.

Let me expand on @Bob 's initial point to argue with you on the same topic.

It is impossible for new miners to enter this subnet, that is a fact. But the problem is not that we cannot replace the top miner who is aggressively registering to protect his position, but that in such a situation you cannot be sure that he really has an excellent solution, the best possible from the point of view of the subnet rating.
Well, judging by his rating of 0.87, which has not changed for at least 2-3 months, I can say that he does not have an ideal solution for the subnet, which could be improved, but will not be, as long as he endlessly knocks out newcomers.

When I was in a similar situation in the position of capturing a subnet, I always gave a chance to newcomers to see if a better solution is possible or not.

It seems like you may not be fully aware of the current state of the subnet.

- First, there's not just a single top miner — at least **three top miners **are actively competing.

- Second, it's **not possible** to achieve a **perfect score**. This is due to the inherent **randomness **in the evaluation process, and it's certainly not the intention of the subnet owner (they're clearly **against overfitting**).

**All top miners are continuously improving, not just sitting still.**

Setting up a registration wall can’t last forever. With the current token price (which is **dropping**), and a registration cost of **0.4**, it takes at least **7 days **to break even on a new key. That means miners who are building a reg wall are essentially sacrificing most of their short-term profits.

At the same time, the testnet is meant to support new miners. They don’t need to spend heavily to register on mainnet right away, and there’s even a dedicated WandB for the testnet — giving them a clear benchmark to compare against the top miners.

I think only 1 - 2 miners are enough for testing. It means you only need 0.5-1 tao for testing your algorithm at maximum.

But there is also a testnet and you can make your own local test environment. After thousands of testing and when you sure about your algorithm's performance, then you can register to mainnet.

If you beats current tops miner, you can increase the number of your miners.

This is the normal approach for bittensor subnet development, isn't it?

What I mean is that you shouldn’t worry about the reg wall. Instead, focus on your best solution—if you demonstrate your strength, the miners who are building the reg wall will start to panic. And then... they will not register new miners anymore continuously.

I don't understand why you all keep going off on unrelated topics.
I introduced a new mechanism and clearly explained its benefits.
So, I expected a discussion or evaluation of its pros and cons.

But instead, you're constantly talking about the top miner.
What's the connection between the top miner and the new mechanism? The top miner will likely stay on top regardless of the mechanism.

👉 
So should I say the real reason you all avoid discussing the new mechanism and instead focus on the top miner - or on me, the "newbie"?

It's because you actually recognize the advantages of the new mechanism and are concerned about it. Under the new system, you might still remain at the top, but it also creates more opportunities for new miners to surpass the current leaders. Am I right?

But from the perspective of the network owner and for the subnet overall, this is clearly a positive step. It encourages algorithm improvements and pushes new miners to develop more powerful solutions.

Your new mechanism isn't new at all, and has been implemented in other subnets.

However, if you look at subnets that have changed their operation method with the mechanism you're discussing, you'll see that the interest of novice miners like you is gradually decreasing, and eventually, they'll transition from popular subnets to exclusive subnets, ultimately leaving them out of the reach of miners.

The same goes for the reg cost issue you're discussing.
A high reg cost indicates high miner interest and competitiveness in the subnet, while a low reg cost indicates a lack of interest from miners.

Finally, I salute the owners and developers who have contributed to the subnet's vitality.
Almost miners have similar performance, in that case, the owner should roll up mechanism by adding more parameters or something like that.

You always use too many unnecessary words.
I don’t think you’re that unrecognizable.

Did I ever say this subnet was cheating? 😂 
I like this subnet - I see it as a great opportunity for growth.

# 🚀 Update: Phase 2, Version 2 🚀
Hey @miid・54, we’ve just rolled out a new update that adds transliterations, addresses, and dates of birth into the workflow. Here’s what’s new:
* Transliterations: We’ll send a non-Latin name → you send back the transliterated version. The validator will also transliterate it and compare the results using the same name-matching metrics as before.

Hello @Asem. @Bromargiza!
There is still issue in address validation logic.
Now the country is fetched from fake library, and validated with geonamescache.
Some country names that are fetched from fake library is not included in geonamescache.
So "city_in_country(gen_city, gen_country)" is always False for those countries.
This makes heuristic_perfect to be False in _grade_address_variations function, so the address score becomes always zero.
I am afraid that I misunderstood something, but this can be issue in the current codebase.
I would appreciate if you check this soon.
